00:00:21.150 --> 00:00:23.220
BOB JONES: I was working
in this consulting firm.

00:00:23.220 --> 00:00:25.410
I got bored.

00:00:25.410 --> 00:00:27.280
I wanted to go start
a business, and I

00:00:27.280 --> 00:00:32.100
said it's not like
I'm in my dorm room.

00:00:32.100 --> 00:00:35.150
It's not like I haven't
done this before,

00:00:35.150 --> 00:00:38.840
so I need to be sensible
about it this time.

00:00:38.840 --> 00:00:41.070
Because I've had
start-ups that succeeded

00:00:41.070 --> 00:00:44.000
and start-ups that failed, and
I like the successes more than

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:45.390
I like the failures.

00:00:45.390 --> 00:00:50.570
So I interviewed a bunch of
people, scientists, marketing

00:00:50.570 --> 00:00:53.390
types, et cetera and came
up with about 15 ideas

00:00:53.390 --> 00:00:55.000
and said that's too many.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.920
I need some filters.

00:00:56.920 --> 00:01:00.320
The first filter was I need
to solve the right problem,

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:01.940
because I'm good
enough at operations

00:01:01.940 --> 00:01:03.315
that I'm going to
hit the target.

00:01:03.315 --> 00:01:06.890
But it's embarrassing if
you pick the wrong target.

00:01:06.890 --> 00:01:09.080
So my definition of
the right problem

00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:11.419
is that you would cheerfully
pay for the solution

00:01:11.419 --> 00:01:12.710
and you will tell your friends.

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:17.400
So I can lower your
cholesterol with

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:18.660
a nutritional intervention.

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:21.600
It's not the right target,
because you don't care.

00:01:21.600 --> 00:01:24.554
You'll forget to take it, your
medication, most of the time,

00:01:24.554 --> 00:01:26.970
and you're never going to talk
about it with your friends.

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:30.170
And I can't afford to educate
you, because I'm a start up.

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:34.510
If your back hurts, ooh, that's
a whole different matter.

00:01:34.510 --> 00:01:36.400
Because if I can help
you with something

00:01:36.400 --> 00:01:38.050
that makes your
back stop hurting,

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:39.356
you will cheerfully pay for it.

00:01:39.356 --> 00:01:40.480
You will tell your friends.

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:42.120
And if furthermore
I can set it up so

00:01:42.120 --> 00:01:46.140
that when you stop taking my
stuff your back starts hurting,

00:01:46.140 --> 00:01:48.370
that's the right target.

00:01:48.370 --> 00:01:52.420
Second filter, I have to
be able solve the problem.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:56.830
So if I had an enzyme
that metabolized gluten,

00:01:56.830 --> 00:02:00.500
I would be speaking to
you today from my yacht.

00:02:00.500 --> 00:02:02.960
So that one's off the table.

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:05.680
That killed all but
about five of the ideas.

00:02:05.680 --> 00:02:09.400
The remaining filter
was somebody besides me

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:11.350
thinks this company
is a cool idea

00:02:11.350 --> 00:02:14.080
and will buy it if
I don't screw it up.

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:17.610
So the last thing I did was
took the remaining ideas

00:02:17.610 --> 00:02:21.450
and called some senior execs
that I was friendly with,

00:02:21.450 --> 00:02:24.190
had companies that
could, well, one day

00:02:24.190 --> 00:02:28.450
buy the business-- Procter
&amp; Gamble, Johnson &amp; Johnson,

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:31.705
Pepsi, et cetera-- and
said, I'm having some ideas.

00:02:31.705 --> 00:02:33.330
I'd like to hear your
thoughts on them.

00:02:33.330 --> 00:02:35.387
I'm not selling anything.

00:02:35.387 --> 00:02:36.970
Well, I knew you
were up to something.

00:02:36.970 --> 00:02:38.340
What are you doing?

00:02:38.340 --> 00:02:40.760
And when I would
offer an idea, if I

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:45.750
would hear crickets and--
OK, on to the next idea.

00:02:45.750 --> 00:02:48.770
That's how we arrived at sleep.

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:51.580
There's somewhere between 50
and 70 million people in the US

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:55.380
that have trouble sleeping,
and they complain about it.

00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.890
And nobody has to tell them
the benefits of a good night's

00:02:57.890 --> 00:02:58.390
sleep.

00:02:58.390 --> 00:03:00.580
Everybody just feels
better, and there

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:03.570
are nutritional interventions
that will solve the problem.

00:03:03.570 --> 00:03:05.280
And the companies
I talked to said

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:07.700
if you don't screw this up,
we'd like to be first in line

00:03:07.700 --> 00:03:10.290
to talk to you in
about two years.

00:03:10.290 --> 00:03:14.720
So with that as background,
I had several businesses

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:16.800
in the past where we
made nutrition bars

00:03:16.800 --> 00:03:18.290
and sold them
through clinicians.

00:03:18.290 --> 00:03:22.360
So my business model was
let's make a nutrition bar,

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:24.850
and let's sell it
through clinicians.

00:03:24.850 --> 00:03:26.392
But I talked to a
number of consumers

00:03:26.392 --> 00:03:28.391
and said, how do you feel
about eating something

00:03:28.391 --> 00:03:30.720
at 10:00 or 10:30 at night
that will have you asleep

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:31.515
a half hour later?

00:03:31.515 --> 00:03:34.800
And most of them said I don't
feel so good about that.

00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:37.560
I don't like the idea
of eating something.

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:39.650
OK, what would you like?

00:03:39.650 --> 00:03:42.950
Well, you know those little
5 Hour Energy drink things?

00:03:42.950 --> 00:03:46.230
Make me one of those, except
with the opposite effect.

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:49.270
Oops, looks like I'm in
the beverage business.

00:03:49.270 --> 00:03:54.230
OK, well so maybe
what I can do here

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:58.230
is find the clinicians that
you are seeing about the fact

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:00.020
that you're having
trouble sleeping,

00:04:00.020 --> 00:04:01.990
and I can do what I did before.

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:04.870
My business model will be I
will call on the clinicians.

00:04:04.870 --> 00:04:06.920
The clinicians will
say, this is fabulous.

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:08.380
I will tell my patients.

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:09.950
The patients will
want to buy it.

00:04:09.950 --> 00:04:11.630
One day I will call Walgreens.

00:04:11.630 --> 00:04:12.520
We'll stock it there.

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:14.920
We've done this before.

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:17.399
You may remember
a little while ago

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:20.060
I said I had a really bad five
or six weeks where everybody

00:04:20.060 --> 00:04:22.220
told me no.

00:04:22.220 --> 00:04:26.910
I called doctors, nurses,
physical therapists,

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:28.090
dietitians.

00:04:28.090 --> 00:04:31.470
I went to assisted living
facilities and retirement

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:34.340
communities and talked to
resident care directors.

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:37.220
And without exception,
I was told no.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:42.440
People don't talk to
their doctor about sleep.

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:44.900
They talk to their doctor
about their ear ache.

00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:47.010
If they do talk to their
doctor about sleep,

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:49.990
the doctor runs for
cover, because he doesn't

00:04:49.990 --> 00:04:51.720
know how to solve the problem.

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:55.110
And he's been trained that this
is a symptom of something else.

00:04:55.110 --> 00:04:57.420
You are depressed and
you need a therapist,

00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:01.140
or you have sleep apnea and you
need one of those Darth Vader

00:05:01.140 --> 00:05:04.210
devices that blows
positive air pressure

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:07.190
and it keeps you
from having apnea.

00:05:07.190 --> 00:05:09.550
So let's refer you to
somebody else next.

00:05:09.550 --> 00:05:11.850
So nobody was willing to
talk about our intervention.

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:17.170
This was the point--
at this point,

00:05:17.170 --> 00:05:19.170
we had made our
minimum viable product,

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:20.890
and we were offering
free samples.

00:05:20.890 --> 00:05:23.860
And they didn't want
it even if it was free,

00:05:23.860 --> 00:05:27.430
so clearly the business
model was flawed.

00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:30.320
We weren't going to be able to
get it into Walgreens or places

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.770
like that if we couldn't
find any customers.

00:05:32.770 --> 00:05:36.150
And the route I had chosen
to get to the customers

00:05:36.150 --> 00:05:37.108
was not working.

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:42.160
Nevertheless, there
were people who

00:05:42.160 --> 00:05:47.520
were calling us back and buying
our minimum viable product.

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:49.360
The one that looks
bad tastes bad,

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:51.330
and because the little
manufacturer spilled

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:54.610
a little solution on the threads
and it dried into something

00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:58.790
like superglue, you need a
vise grips to get the cap off.

00:05:58.790 --> 00:06:01.960
People were buying it anyway.

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:04.810
Clearly we had
something there, so it

00:06:04.810 --> 00:06:08.030
was time to address the business
model of what is it we have,

00:06:08.030 --> 00:06:11.920
and to whom should we be
marketing it, and how.

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:16.670
Along the way I ended up in a
conversation with Whole Foods.

00:06:16.670 --> 00:06:19.740
Because when I was running
a soy foods company

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:23.980
I sold a lot of tofu to
them, and I knew them.

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:24.860
So I thought, oh, OK.

00:06:24.860 --> 00:06:25.860
We'll put this together.

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:28.270
We'll sell it
through Whole Foods.

00:06:28.270 --> 00:06:30.820
But who is our customer?

00:06:30.820 --> 00:06:33.860
We did a lot of work,
a lot of interviews,

00:06:33.860 --> 00:06:37.270
got told no some
more and concluded

00:06:37.270 --> 00:06:39.540
that there are a number
of niche markets here

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:40.540
that we could work with.

00:06:40.540 --> 00:06:44.640
But the one where we were going
to start was working moms,

00:06:44.640 --> 00:06:48.710
and not working moms who have
infants or toddlers at home.

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:51.040
They expect to be
tired, and they

00:06:51.040 --> 00:06:53.656
want to be able to wake
up if the baby's not

00:06:53.656 --> 00:06:54.780
sleeping through the night.

00:06:54.780 --> 00:06:55.720
So forget it.

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:58.250
But once their kids are
preschool, kindergarten,

00:06:58.250 --> 00:07:03.410
or older, they've got
the hardest job on earth.

00:07:03.410 --> 00:07:05.500
Most of them have
husbands who don't shop,

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:10.740
don't cook, don't pick up their
socks, so they're hardworking.

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:12.450
They're daytime professionals.

00:07:12.450 --> 00:07:13.945
They're fussy
about what they buy

00:07:13.945 --> 00:07:15.320
and what they
bring in the house.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:16.720
They do shop at Whole Foods.

00:07:16.720 --> 00:07:18.670
It looks like the
right market for us.

00:07:18.670 --> 00:07:24.050
So in my conversation
with Whole Foods,

00:07:24.050 --> 00:07:25.820
I was pretty direct
with them and said,

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:28.450
look, I can live a
long and happy life

00:07:28.450 --> 00:07:30.567
and never put my
products on your shelf.

00:07:30.567 --> 00:07:32.900
The moral of the point, I
don't want to be on your shelf

00:07:32.900 --> 00:07:34.590
if it doesn't make sense.

00:07:34.590 --> 00:07:37.010
So really the purpose of
this meeting in my view

00:07:37.010 --> 00:07:39.070
is to figure out will
it ever make sense

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:41.490
and if so, what's
the trigger point.

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:45.150
And the answer to that was
when we see enough reorders

00:07:45.150 --> 00:07:51.660
through Amazon to show
that there's a there there,

00:07:51.660 --> 00:07:53.030
come back and see them.

00:07:53.030 --> 00:07:53.797
Keep them posted.

00:07:53.797 --> 00:07:54.880
They'll remain interested.

00:07:54.880 --> 00:07:59.080
We are after all friends,
and it's a provocative idea.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:01.980
So the revised business
model now having

00:08:01.980 --> 00:08:04.540
gone through this
postulate the idea,

00:08:04.540 --> 00:08:06.240
develop a minimum
viable product,

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:08.010
shake it down in
the marketplace,

00:08:08.010 --> 00:08:12.390
identify the target is
we're reaching working

00:08:12.390 --> 00:08:15.290
moms via mommy bloggers.

00:08:15.290 --> 00:08:17.420
We've identified 100
of them, some of whom

00:08:17.420 --> 00:08:20.550
have as many as
100,000 followers.

00:08:20.550 --> 00:08:22.640
There's also all manner
of social media ways

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:23.980
to reach working moms.

00:08:23.980 --> 00:08:26.540
So working moms,
we're reaching them.

00:08:26.540 --> 00:08:29.250
We're selling the product
through our website which

00:08:29.250 --> 00:08:32.039
will be a minuscule
percentage and through Amazon

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:35.730
until such point as we have
enough of a reorder stream

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:39.250
to make a justifiable
approach to Whole Foods

00:08:39.250 --> 00:08:40.799
and other retailers.

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:44.590
Shortly after that, we
hope to sell the business.

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:48.580
So Rich, that's sort of an
impromptu summary of how

00:08:48.580 --> 00:08:51.200
our business model
morphed and pivoted,

00:08:51.200 --> 00:08:53.240
and it's a work in process.

00:08:53.240 --> 00:08:56.328
So if you don't have anything
else to do, wish us luck.

00:08:56.328 --> 00:08:57.244
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:59.925 --> 00:09:00.800
BOB JONES: Thank you.

00:09:04.245 --> 00:09:05.620
PROFESSOR: So the
reason I wanted

00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:08.810
Bob to tell you about
that is to reemphasize

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:11.670
this is not just an
academic exercise.

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:14.660
He told you about how
he succeeded before.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:16.430
He told you how he
failed the first time.

00:09:16.430 --> 00:09:18.020
He did something
different the second.

00:09:18.020 --> 00:09:20.320
He took the second model
into the third market,

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:23.570
which turned out not to be the
right thing for that market.

00:09:23.570 --> 00:09:24.730
And he's reinventing it.

00:09:24.730 --> 00:09:27.280
And it's been an
interesting thing.

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:30.290
So what we say up here,
we're not giving you

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:31.490
a formula on how to do it.

00:09:31.490 --> 00:09:34.270
We're trying to get you to think
about these kind of issues,

00:09:34.270 --> 00:09:37.640
and this is an example
of an in-process thing.

00:09:37.640 --> 00:09:40.690
And it's been an
interesting route.

00:09:40.690 --> 00:09:47.550
Bob, any other comments or
people from the audience?

00:09:47.550 --> 00:09:49.390
BOB JONES: It's
practically a reality TV

