some insights with you.

00:18:51.670 --> 00:18:54.480
Essentially this is how
I think of these things.

00:18:54.480 --> 00:18:57.680
We start off with a whole
bunch of disparate data points.

00:18:57.680 --> 00:18:59.630
We call that information.

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:02.520
Hopefully we begin to
connect those dots.

00:19:02.520 --> 00:19:06.310
It's almost like a
pointillist painting, where

00:19:06.310 --> 00:19:07.667
you have thousands of dots.

00:19:07.667 --> 00:19:09.250
And then slowly as
they come together,

00:19:09.250 --> 00:19:10.220
they start to connect.

00:19:10.220 --> 00:19:12.320
And then ultimately out
of that, you have wisdom.

00:19:12.320 --> 00:19:15.850
You have an image that
is created out of that.

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:17.520
What I hope to do
today is provide you

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:19.850
each of those three--
information, knowledge,

00:19:19.850 --> 00:19:21.300
and wisdom.

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:23.880
So let's start off with
a simple foundation.

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:28.300
And the foundation is to
say this-- many definitions

00:19:28.300 --> 00:19:30.181
of a business model exist.

00:19:30.181 --> 00:19:32.430
The one that I like the most
is simply this-- a method

00:19:32.430 --> 00:19:34.970
by which a firm uses
its resources-- cash,

00:19:34.970 --> 00:19:38.160
technology, its people-- to
offer its customers better

00:19:38.160 --> 00:19:43.100
value than its competitors,
and make money doing so.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:46.846
It tells who pays how much,
and how often do they pay.

00:19:46.846 --> 00:19:48.220
For those of you
that are looking

00:19:48.220 --> 00:19:51.810
to start companies, or even
begin to work for companies,

00:19:51.810 --> 00:19:53.560
especially
early-stage companies,

00:19:53.560 --> 00:19:55.690
the question that the
board, the investors,

00:19:55.690 --> 00:19:58.870
the new employee coming in
the door are going to ask

00:19:58.870 --> 00:20:00.500
is, what do you do?

00:20:00.500 --> 00:20:01.380
Who do you sell to?

00:20:01.380 --> 00:20:03.430
And how do you make money?

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:05.360
It's pretty simple.

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:07.460
The how do you make
money part is often

00:20:07.460 --> 00:20:09.500
the challenge for
many start-ups.

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:11.016
They have very cool technology.

00:20:11.016 --> 00:20:13.440
They think they know
who's going to buy it.

00:20:13.440 --> 00:20:14.820
But they have no
idea how they're

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:17.392
going to get it in the
hands of those individuals.

00:20:17.392 --> 00:20:18.850
Are they going to
create a website?

00:20:18.850 --> 00:20:21.710
Are they going to join--
sign on to the app store?

00:20:21.710 --> 00:20:23.520
Are they going to go retail?

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:25.090
Are they going to
use a distribution

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:26.440
channel or partner?

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:28.627
That's the big crux of it.

00:20:28.627 --> 00:20:31.210
So that's the question you have
to continue to think about is,

00:20:31.210 --> 00:20:35.960
how do we ultimately make money
from what we are developing?

00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:38.730
So what's changed
a lot in the way

00:20:38.730 --> 00:20:41.800
we operate in this world is
the way that companies operate,

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:44.244
the way that companies
are formed and developed.

00:20:44.244 --> 00:20:46.410
And this chart is not really
meant, in great detail,

00:20:46.410 --> 00:20:46.910
to be read.

00:20:46.910 --> 00:20:48.910
But overall, what
you have here is

00:20:48.910 --> 00:20:53.790
an example of how over time, you
have points of history where,

00:20:53.790 --> 00:20:56.840
as industries
developed, changed,

00:20:56.840 --> 00:21:00.810
they went away, what you had is
different ways of communicating

00:21:00.810 --> 00:21:03.970
with the world, different
ways of actually connecting

00:21:03.970 --> 00:21:05.570
with consumers.

00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:09.250
If you think about back in the
days of merchants and mechanics

00:21:09.250 --> 00:21:11.700
and industrial
businesses, the way

00:21:11.700 --> 00:21:14.740
they operated and communicated
was much different.

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:18.510
Retail stores existed, but in a
very, very, very different way.

00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:20.820
They were family-run stores.

00:21:20.820 --> 00:21:23.350
Most of the products and
services we bought from

00:21:23.350 --> 00:21:25.790
were from a few large
retailers like Sears,

00:21:25.790 --> 00:21:27.490
whether that be your
washer and dryer

00:21:27.490 --> 00:21:30.100
or your tools or other things.

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:33.590
As technology continued
to mature, what you saw

00:21:33.590 --> 00:21:35.970
is the financial service
industry becoming very, very

00:21:35.970 --> 00:21:37.144
sophisticated.

00:21:37.144 --> 00:21:38.560
And the financial
service industry

00:21:38.560 --> 00:21:44.800
began to allow us to see
business in a global way.

00:21:44.800 --> 00:21:48.210
Out of that came complex
advertising campaigns,

00:21:48.210 --> 00:21:50.740
global marketing and
distribution mechanisms.

00:21:50.740 --> 00:21:55.480
And what you saw is entirely
new ways to buy and reach

00:21:55.480 --> 00:21:58.120
the end user, the products.

00:21:58.120 --> 00:22:00.580
What really changed is,
at this end of the world,

00:22:00.580 --> 00:22:06.160
where you had technology, was
then introduced in such a way

00:22:06.160 --> 00:22:09.855
that distribution of goods--
ultimately the ability

00:22:09.855 --> 00:22:12.590
to connect an individual
who wants a product

00:22:12.590 --> 00:22:15.240
or service to that
product or service--

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:18.600
the barriers of distance,
the barriers of manufacturing

00:22:18.600 --> 00:22:20.012
suddenly went away.

00:22:20.012 --> 00:22:21.970
The United States has
probably done this better

00:22:21.970 --> 00:22:24.520
than almost any
place in the world.

00:22:24.520 --> 00:22:26.920
We can get something
delivered tomorrow

00:22:26.920 --> 00:22:30.380
that we ordered this afternoon
at 11:00 AM or 1 o'clock

00:22:30.380 --> 00:22:35.440
in the afternoon, whether it be
a product or service, because

00:22:35.440 --> 00:22:38.860
of financial support and
backing for those type

00:22:38.860 --> 00:22:42.740
of organizations, whether it
be the manufacturers, the UPS,

00:22:42.740 --> 00:22:44.450
the FedEx, and others.

00:22:44.450 --> 00:22:47.654
The distribution channels
have shrunk greatly.

00:22:47.654 --> 00:22:49.570
When I travel to different
parts of the world,

00:22:49.570 --> 00:22:55.200
they find an amazing selection
of products and services

00:22:55.200 --> 00:22:57.000
that we have in
the United States.

00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:00.170
And when you go elsewhere,
you notice how limited it is.

00:23:00.170 --> 00:23:01.670
If you're living
in parts of Europe,

00:23:01.670 --> 00:23:03.330
if you're living
in parts of Africa,

00:23:03.330 --> 00:23:06.570
parts of Asia, if you're
living in most of Russia--

00:23:06.570 --> 00:23:08.520
the ability to actually
order something today

00:23:08.520 --> 00:23:14.470
and see it arrives in the next
month is very, very unlikely.

00:23:14.470 --> 00:23:16.470
And the more remote you
are, the less likely

00:23:16.470 --> 00:23:18.060
it is it's ever
going to reach you

00:23:18.060 --> 00:23:20.850
on time, or without
being lost in some part

00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:22.260
of the distribution channel.

00:23:22.260 --> 00:23:24.260
So I encourage you
to think about,

00:23:24.260 --> 00:23:26.860
as technology has changed
and distribution channels

00:23:26.860 --> 00:23:29.280
have changed, it has
impacted the way that we

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:32.020
operate and build companies.

00:23:32.020 --> 00:23:34.540
So at MIT, when we
think about how do you

00:23:34.540 --> 00:23:37.070
bring a company from
the idea to the market,

00:23:37.070 --> 00:23:40.670
or what is so often called
the lab to the market, the way

00:23:40.670 --> 00:23:44.657
you think about that has to
integrate the business model.

00:23:44.657 --> 00:23:47.115
So for those of you here that
are scientists or researchers

00:23:47.115 --> 00:23:50.340
or engineers, as you're thinking
about your new products,

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:51.770
your service, or
your technology,

00:23:51.770 --> 00:23:55.630
you have to continually test
who is going to buy this.

00:23:55.630 --> 00:23:58.110
How am I going to get
it to the consumer?

00:23:58.110 --> 00:24:01.520
How will this ultimately impact
the people that I care about,

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:03.020
the people that are
going to benefit

00:24:03.020 --> 00:24:05.485
from my product or my service?

