of failures and challenges,

00:24:57.070 --> 00:24:59.780
whether it be because of
market acceptance, technology

00:24:59.780 --> 00:25:01.890
failures, or it
happens just simply

00:25:01.890 --> 00:25:07.116
because the market was not
ready for what you were doing.

00:25:07.116 --> 00:25:08.490
The goal is for
you to figure out

00:25:08.490 --> 00:25:10.990
throughout those
bumps and those curves

00:25:10.990 --> 00:25:13.340
how to identify
opportunity, and also

00:25:13.340 --> 00:25:15.820
how to modify your
products and services.

00:25:15.820 --> 00:25:18.477
So that brings us to
business models in general.

00:25:18.477 --> 00:25:20.810
There's lots of different
ways to think about a business

00:25:20.810 --> 00:25:21.900
model.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:24.150
Complexity was famous for years.

00:25:24.150 --> 00:25:25.940
I remember when I was
in graduate school,

00:25:25.940 --> 00:25:27.780
they would talk about
business models, sales

00:25:27.780 --> 00:25:29.440
and marketing and distribution.

00:25:29.440 --> 00:25:32.370
And it was mind boggling.

00:25:32.370 --> 00:25:35.227
If they pass it out on
an 8 1/2 x 11 sheet,

00:25:35.227 --> 00:25:37.560
you would need a magnifying
glass to figure out what was

00:25:37.560 --> 00:25:40.650
happening because the
distribution channels were not

00:25:40.650 --> 00:25:41.450
as sophisticated.

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:44.420
The technology was
not as sophisticated.

00:25:44.420 --> 00:25:46.430
So you had complex models.

00:25:46.430 --> 00:25:48.830
And within these
complex models, there

00:25:48.830 --> 00:25:51.300
were lots of points
of failure, lots

00:25:51.300 --> 00:25:54.212
of points where your reseller
or your OEM channel--

00:25:54.212 --> 00:25:55.795
your original equipment
manufacturer--

00:25:55.795 --> 00:25:58.472
or your distributor
was failing, lots

00:25:58.472 --> 00:26:00.180
of points where the
manufacturing was not

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:03.530
succeeding or the retail
environment was struggling.

00:26:03.530 --> 00:26:06.220
So what's happened is you've
seen simplification of business

00:26:06.220 --> 00:26:10.150
models-- these ideas that
become simplified in such a way

00:26:10.150 --> 00:26:13.580
where you say to yourself,
I'm building this,

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:16.260
and I want it to be in
the hands of these people,

00:26:16.260 --> 00:26:19.500
whether that be a consumer, a
doctor, a lawyer, if it happens

00:26:19.500 --> 00:26:21.300
to be a large corporation.

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:24.060
What's the easiest
way to get there?

00:26:24.060 --> 00:26:26.036
And leveraging
technology, leveraging

00:26:26.036 --> 00:26:27.660
all of those things
that are out there,

00:26:27.660 --> 00:26:30.010
including the good advice
of experienced people,

00:26:30.010 --> 00:26:32.000
will help simplify this.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.450
An example might be
Zipcar, a company

00:26:34.450 --> 00:26:36.880
we're all very familiar with.

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:39.450
This is a relatively
simple business model.

00:26:39.450 --> 00:26:41.460
It almost seems so
simple that you'd

00:26:41.460 --> 00:26:45.620
be amazed if you presented
this to an investor and said,

00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:46.530
this is our model.

00:26:46.530 --> 00:26:47.470
This is it.

00:26:47.470 --> 00:26:49.510
And we're going to build
basically a company

00:26:49.510 --> 00:26:52.250
worth-- a publicly traded
company-- I don't even

00:26:52.250 --> 00:26:55.700
know what the market
cap is at right now.

00:26:55.700 --> 00:26:58.270
Fantastic, successful
organization,

00:26:58.270 --> 00:27:01.610
operating globally in many
cities around the world.

00:27:01.610 --> 00:27:04.170
They kept it very simple,
very organized business model.

00:27:04.170 --> 00:27:07.710
How many people
here use Dropbox?

00:27:07.710 --> 00:27:10.170
You get 2/3 of the group
here that use Dropbox.

00:27:10.170 --> 00:27:15.050
When's the last time you saw
a Dropbox advertisement on TV?

00:27:15.050 --> 00:27:16.500
It doesn't exist.

00:27:16.500 --> 00:27:18.800
20 years ago, if you were
looking to build a company,

00:27:18.800 --> 00:27:20.650
you'd have to have an
advertising budget.

00:27:20.650 --> 00:27:21.580
You'd have to think
about how we're

00:27:21.580 --> 00:27:23.290
going to wind up getting
this into the hands

00:27:23.290 --> 00:27:23.910
of the right people.

00:27:23.910 --> 00:27:24.860
Who are the right people?

00:27:24.860 --> 00:27:26.318
Are we going to
sell to businesses?

00:27:26.318 --> 00:27:28.200
Are we going to
sell to individuals?

00:27:28.200 --> 00:27:30.340
What's Dropbox's business model?

00:27:30.340 --> 00:27:34.460
How come you guys know
so much about Dropbox?

00:27:34.460 --> 00:27:36.160
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:36.160 --> 00:27:37.890
RICH KIVEL: How was that?

00:27:37.890 --> 00:27:38.524
Word of mouth.

00:27:38.524 --> 00:27:39.440
Other people told you.

00:27:39.440 --> 00:27:40.639
It's viral.

00:27:40.639 --> 00:27:42.680
So somebody tells you
about this incredible thing

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:43.410
called Dropbox.

00:27:43.410 --> 00:27:45.030
You can sign up for free.

00:27:45.030 --> 00:27:48.380
You can get a certain amount
of megabits of space for free.

00:27:48.380 --> 00:27:50.380
And all of a sudden, you
start uploading photos.

00:27:50.380 --> 00:27:52.755
Or you're sharing PowerPoint
presentations and documents.

00:27:52.755 --> 00:27:53.797
And your friend signs on.

00:27:53.797 --> 00:27:56.088
And then all of a sudden,
you tell three other friends.

00:27:56.088 --> 00:27:56.970
And they sign on.

00:27:56.970 --> 00:27:59.920
And then all of a sudden,
when that is shown as viable,

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:03.490
before you know it, they've
got an entire model here

00:28:03.490 --> 00:28:07.210
that is making them a
fortune, because they now

00:28:07.210 --> 00:28:09.960
have businesses and
large-- what they call

00:28:09.960 --> 00:28:13.410
Pro subscribers, large
users-- paying large dollars

00:28:13.410 --> 00:28:15.570
in order to access that data.

00:28:15.570 --> 00:28:16.620
It's fantastic.

00:28:16.620 --> 00:28:19.630
Does that look like a
complicated business model?

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:21.710
No, not really.

00:28:21.710 --> 00:28:25.450
Here's another example
of simplicity rules.

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:28.340
We have the luxury of
leveraging technology.

00:28:28.340 --> 00:28:32.210
And we also have different types
of mechanisms in order for us

00:28:32.210 --> 00:28:34.152
to educate consumers.

00:28:34.152 --> 00:28:35.860
Viral marketing is
certainly one of those

00:28:35.860 --> 00:28:37.170
we'll talk about today.

00:28:37.170 --> 00:28:40.210
So simply put, your business
model is not your business.

00:28:40.210 --> 00:28:41.640
Please remember that.

00:28:41.640 --> 00:28:44.090
The business model and
business model innovation

00:28:44.090 --> 00:28:47.580
is critical in developing
a quality business,

00:28:47.580 --> 00:28:50.150
attacking new markets and
driving profitability.

00:28:50.150 --> 00:28:52.950
Just as Bob had shared
earlier, the ability

00:28:52.950 --> 00:28:57.880
to modify change and
dwarf your business model

00:28:57.880 --> 00:29:02.539
is critical because
just one small change

00:29:02.539 --> 00:29:03.830
can make all of the difference.

00:29:03.830 --> 00:29:04.990
And we're going to talk
about some companies that

00:29:04.990 --> 00:29:06.420
made small changes.

00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:08.680
And it's made all of the
difference in their success.

00:29:08.680 --> 00:29:12.080
So I'll do the academic
part of this presentation

00:29:12.080 --> 00:29:14.250
to give you components
of the business model.

00:29:14.250 --> 00:29:17.830
Then we're going to talk
about some good examples.

00:29:17.830 --> 00:29:20.360
And then I'm going to leave
plenty of time for Q&amp;A,

00:29:20.360 --> 00:29:23.350
and end on time,
as I promised Joe.

00:29:23.350 --> 00:29:24.970
So from a business
model perspective,

00:29:24.970 --> 00:29:26.095
there's lots of components.

00:29:26.095 --> 00:29:28.840
There's aspects of a business
model that should exist.

00:29:28.840 --> 00:29:31.200
Overall, they're pretty simple.

00:29:31.200 --> 00:29:32.920
What is the value proposition?

00:29:32.920 --> 00:29:35.250
What are the market segments
that you're targeting?

00:29:35.250 --> 00:29:36.580
What is the value chain?

00:29:36.580 --> 00:29:38.660
And what is the structure
of that value chain?

00:29:38.660 --> 00:29:40.620
Who's involved in it?

00:29:40.620 --> 00:29:42.980
What is your position
within that value network?

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:44.550
Are you at the
early, early stage

00:29:44.550 --> 00:29:46.250
from a standpoint
of manufacturing?

00:29:46.250 --> 00:29:49.059
Are you at the end stage
from a standpoint of actually

00:29:49.059 --> 00:29:51.100
delivering the product or
service to the consumer

00:29:51.100 --> 00:29:53.150
or are you somewhere
in the middle?

00:29:53.150 --> 00:29:55.160
How do you generate revenue?

00:29:55.160 --> 00:29:57.100
And how do you generate margins?

00:29:57.100 --> 00:29:59.461
And those are two
very different things.

00:29:59.461 --> 00:30:00.960
There are companies
out there we all

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:03.610
know that generate tremendous
amounts of revenue.

00:30:03.610 --> 00:30:07.590
And their margins are very
tiny-- 1%, half a percent

00:30:07.590 --> 00:30:08.940
or less.

00:30:08.940 --> 00:30:11.414
But they make it up because
the revenue is so extreme.

00:30:11.414 --> 00:30:12.830
You have other
companies out there

00:30:12.830 --> 00:30:15.840
that have exceptionally
high margins, tremendously

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:19.470
high margins, not
very large revenues.

00:30:19.470 --> 00:30:22.680
Think about luxury
goods resellers.

00:30:22.680 --> 00:30:25.360
Take a look at the
average consumer

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:29.180
that goes out and buys a
luxury bag or a nice suit

00:30:29.180 --> 00:30:31.840
or an expensive watch.

00:30:31.840 --> 00:30:33.820
Well I can go buy a
watch from Movado.

00:30:33.820 --> 00:30:36.704
Or I can go buy a
watch from Swatch.

00:30:36.704 --> 00:30:37.870
These are beautiful watches.

00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:40.530
They're made by large
manufacturing groups.

00:30:40.530 --> 00:30:43.120
They're going through a very,
very sophisticated distribution

00:30:43.120 --> 00:30:43.680
channel.

00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:46.520
And they're made in
the tens of thousands.

00:30:46.520 --> 00:30:49.270
Those watches are sold
anywhere between $39.00,

00:30:49.270 --> 00:30:52.480
$49.00 up to probably $1,000.00.

00:30:52.480 --> 00:30:54.650
And they're sold
in the thousands

00:30:54.650 --> 00:30:57.360
through retailers that
you see in the mall,

00:30:57.360 --> 00:30:59.080
through retailers
that are online,

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:01.850
and also through big-box
sellers like Walmart

00:31:01.850 --> 00:31:04.682
or Costco or others.

00:31:04.682 --> 00:31:06.140
You think, wow,
that's interesting.

00:31:06.140 --> 00:31:09.190
Someone like Swatch and also
Movado, which is much higher

00:31:09.190 --> 00:31:12.590
end, they both sell through
similar distribution channels.

00:31:12.590 --> 00:31:14.380
They do tremendous volume.

00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:17.040
So they have very,
very high revenues.

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:19.760
But their margins
are incredibly small.

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:22.070
The goal is saturate the market.

00:31:22.070 --> 00:31:24.780
Get as many people
to buy as possible.

00:31:24.780 --> 00:31:26.520
Take a look at other
types of products

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:28.990
that are similar that
are called watches.

00:31:28.990 --> 00:31:31.430
Very often they're
then called timepieces,

00:31:31.430 --> 00:31:35.750
where you have watches that
are handmade, where they're

00:31:35.750 --> 00:31:38.130
made in a very, very
subtle way, where it's

00:31:38.130 --> 00:31:42.890
a lot of on-hand or craftsman
work and craftsman design,

00:31:42.890 --> 00:31:45.320
very low on the
manufacturing side.

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:47.660
It might take months to
make a particular watch,

00:31:47.660 --> 00:31:48.861
if not longer.

00:31:48.861 --> 00:31:51.110
And the watches sell for
tens of thousands or hundreds

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:52.600
of thousands of dollars.

00:31:52.600 --> 00:31:55.400
You think about
IWC, Patek Philippe.

00:31:55.400 --> 00:31:59.200
Many of these watches will sell
for $100,000.00 or $50,000.00

00:31:59.200 --> 00:32:00.850
for a watch.

00:32:00.850 --> 00:32:03.630
Totally different
business model.

00:32:03.630 --> 00:32:06.020
Their margins are very large.

00:32:06.020 --> 00:32:08.680
But their overall revenues are
relatively small because they

00:32:08.680 --> 00:32:11.080
don't sell a lot of pieces.

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:13.140
Think about Mercedes-Benz.

00:32:13.140 --> 00:32:16.510
And think about Ford.

00:32:16.510 --> 00:32:19.900
If you base success on the
total number of vehicles sold,

00:32:19.900 --> 00:32:23.800
Ford kills them year
in and year out.

00:32:23.800 --> 00:32:27.310
If you base it on margins,
slightly different story.

00:32:27.310 --> 00:32:29.670
Ford has some products that
are incredibly high margins,

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:31.120
like their SUVs.

00:32:31.120 --> 00:32:33.167
They have other products,
like their low-end cars

00:32:33.167 --> 00:32:34.250
that are very low margins.

00:32:34.250 --> 00:32:35.750
But they're looking
to get adoption

00:32:35.750 --> 00:32:37.990
within a particular marketplace.

00:32:37.990 --> 00:32:40.200
Mercedes, much different story.

00:32:40.200 --> 00:32:44.160
Very high margins on virtually
every vehicle they sell.

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:47.102
Much lower volume.

00:32:47.102 --> 00:32:49.560
So all of these things have to
be taken into consideration.

00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:53.590
You cannot choose your business
model because it seemed like it

00:32:53.590 --> 00:32:56.300
made sense, because you
saw a competitor doing it.

00:32:56.300 --> 00:32:58.070
You have to figure
out where are you

00:32:58.070 --> 00:33:00.770
within that particular
value network.

00:33:00.770 --> 00:33:02.540
The competitive strategy
plays into that,

00:33:02.540 --> 00:33:04.710
and what stage of
development is the company.

00:33:04.710 --> 00:33:06.960
So I'm going to flip through
a couple of these slides.

00:33:06.960 --> 00:33:08.180
And we'll dive
into some examples.

00:33:08.180 --> 00:33:09.555
And I'm hoping
you guys have lots

00:33:09.555 --> 00:33:10.830
of questions at that point.

00:33:10.830 --> 00:33:15.080
So the value proposition, which
is really number one here,

00:33:15.080 --> 00:33:17.870
is really a description
of the customer problem,

00:33:17.870 --> 00:33:19.830
the solution that
addresses that problem,

00:33:19.830 --> 00:33:22.520
and the value of the
solution from the customer's

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:24.220
perspective.

00:33:24.220 --> 00:33:27.185
The customer's perspective
is very important here.

00:33:27.185 --> 00:33:30.040
If I am buying, let's
say an Apple product,

00:33:30.040 --> 00:33:33.200
which I see a lot of here,
well there's a lot of things

00:33:33.200 --> 00:33:36.260
there that I as a consumer
might be attracted to.

00:33:36.260 --> 00:33:39.010
I love the design of it, the
size of it, the feel of it,

00:33:39.010 --> 00:33:40.850
the way it operates.

00:33:40.850 --> 00:33:44.390
If, for example, you're
buying a desktop computer,

00:33:44.390 --> 00:33:46.310
and you chose to
pick out a Dell,

00:33:46.310 --> 00:33:48.870
or you chose to pick out
another type of manufacturer,

00:33:48.870 --> 00:33:50.710
not like Apple--
maybe you're buying it

00:33:50.710 --> 00:33:53.830
for entirely different
reasons than that Apple user.

00:33:53.830 --> 00:33:56.620
So think about what is it
that the customer perceives

00:33:56.620 --> 00:33:57.800
as value.

00:33:57.800 --> 00:34:01.500
Is the customer looking for low
cost or are they looking for

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:03.259
speed?

00:34:03.259 --> 00:34:04.550
Are they looking for something?

00:34:04.550 --> 00:34:07.880
You need to make sure that your
value proposition offers that.

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:10.050
From a market
segmentation perspective,

00:34:10.050 --> 00:34:11.280
it's choosing your audience.

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:15.440
And we could talk about this
entirely throughout this class.

00:34:15.440 --> 00:34:16.840
But I'm going to keep it short.

00:34:16.840 --> 00:34:19.630
You have to know who that
ultimate end user is.

00:34:19.630 --> 00:34:21.909
Who is that person that's
going to write that check,

00:34:21.909 --> 00:34:23.889
recognizing that different
market segments have

00:34:23.889 --> 00:34:25.164
different needs.

00:34:25.164 --> 00:34:26.830
If you're selling,
we'll use the example

00:34:26.830 --> 00:34:29.889
I did a moment ago-- if you're
selling to that high-end watch

00:34:29.889 --> 00:34:33.780
buyer, who's buying
essentially a timepiece that's

00:34:33.780 --> 00:34:36.684
going to be passed down
for generations, that's

00:34:36.684 --> 00:34:39.100
a different type of buyer, a
different type of a marketing

00:34:39.100 --> 00:34:43.460
approach than if you're
selling a Swatch watch, which

00:34:43.460 --> 00:34:45.590
borders on a disposable watch.

00:34:45.590 --> 00:34:47.520
If it lasts five
years, it's fantastic.

00:34:47.520 --> 00:34:49.478
By then, you probably
have bought three or four

00:34:49.478 --> 00:34:50.310
more watches.

00:34:50.310 --> 00:34:53.670
Same thing for computers and
cars and many other things.

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:55.239
Additionally value
change structure

00:34:55.239 --> 00:34:57.800
and position in the value
network are critical to this.

00:34:57.800 --> 00:34:59.920
And they're part of that
initial slide I shared.

00:34:59.920 --> 00:35:02.172
So what is the firm's
position in the value chain?

00:35:02.172 --> 00:35:04.130
What are the activities
within the value chain?

00:35:04.130 --> 00:35:07.390
And how the firm will
capture part of the value

00:35:07.390 --> 00:35:09.864
that it creates
within that chain,

00:35:09.864 --> 00:35:12.280
because where you fit within
that chain and how much of it

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:15.920
you own is really,
really important to know.

00:35:15.920 --> 00:35:18.070
If you're Netflix
think about where

00:35:18.070 --> 00:35:20.500
are you in the value chain.

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:22.304
AUDIENCE: Describe
the value chain.

00:35:22.304 --> 00:35:23.220
RICH KIVEL: Excellent.

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:26.090
So you asked if I could
describe the value chain.

00:35:26.090 --> 00:35:28.702
So think about the entire cycle.

00:35:28.702 --> 00:35:30.160
And I'll use Netflix
as an example,

00:35:30.160 --> 00:35:31.220
because I mentioned it.

00:35:31.220 --> 00:35:34.260
So what does Netflix
do, essentially?

00:35:34.260 --> 00:35:35.760
AUDIENCE: They're distribution.

00:35:35.760 --> 00:35:37.134
RICH KIVEL: They're
distribution.

00:35:37.134 --> 00:35:38.749
To who?

00:35:38.749 --> 00:35:39.540
AUDIENCE: End user.

00:35:39.540 --> 00:35:40.581
RICH KIVEL: The end user.

00:35:40.581 --> 00:35:42.392
They are at the far
end, whichever end

00:35:42.392 --> 00:35:43.600
you want to call the far end.

00:35:43.600 --> 00:35:45.410
They're at the far
end of the cycle.

00:35:45.410 --> 00:35:47.530
There's not much after that.

00:35:47.530 --> 00:35:52.970
They're distributing a movie,
something entertaining, to us.

00:35:52.970 --> 00:35:54.470
If you think about
that entire value

00:35:54.470 --> 00:35:58.980
chain or that entire cycle,
it goes all the way back,

00:35:58.980 --> 00:36:02.740
way, way, way back to
somebody, maybe a year ago

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:06.270
or 20 years ago that had an
idea for a picture, an idea

00:36:06.270 --> 00:36:09.740
for a movie or a
film, who then as they

00:36:09.740 --> 00:36:11.890
moved through that
value chain, maybe

00:36:11.890 --> 00:36:13.390
they found a screenwriter.

00:36:13.390 --> 00:36:15.600
They ultimately,
perhaps, found a studio.

00:36:15.600 --> 00:36:17.420
That studio ultimately
made a decision

00:36:17.420 --> 00:36:19.590
whether they were going
to fund it or not,

00:36:19.590 --> 00:36:21.930
just like a venture capitalist.

00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:26.620
Movies are just like starting
companies-- idea, all the way

00:36:26.620 --> 00:36:29.510
through to the business
plan to the funding.

00:36:29.510 --> 00:36:32.020
That venture capitalist,
or in the case of a movie,

00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:34.340
it's the studio that
says, we love it.

00:36:34.340 --> 00:36:35.050
We want it.

00:36:35.050 --> 00:36:37.260
The story's outstanding.

00:36:37.260 --> 00:36:38.324
We want to buy the story.

00:36:38.324 --> 00:36:39.990
We're going to put
this much against it.

00:36:39.990 --> 00:36:43.540
They then build the team.

00:36:43.540 --> 00:36:45.260
So they find who's
going to be the lead.

00:36:45.260 --> 00:36:46.250
Who's going to be the second?

00:36:46.250 --> 00:36:47.090
Who's going to be the third?

00:36:47.090 --> 00:36:48.280
Who's going to the
action character?

00:36:48.280 --> 00:36:49.880
Who's going to be the romantic?

00:36:49.880 --> 00:36:51.250
Where is it going to be filmed?

00:36:51.250 --> 00:36:54.150
All of these aspects are
just like a business.

00:36:54.150 --> 00:36:56.760
They've got to find the
CEO, the CFO, the CTO.

00:36:56.760 --> 00:36:57.554
They have to figure
out where are we

00:36:57.554 --> 00:36:58.720
going to locate the company.

00:36:58.720 --> 00:37:01.190
Where's the best
place for it to be?

00:37:01.190 --> 00:37:03.540
And then at that point,
they start working on it,

00:37:03.540 --> 00:37:05.330
and toiling away,
and filming it.

00:37:05.330 --> 00:37:08.680
And filming could take
weeks, months, or even years.

00:37:08.680 --> 00:37:11.630
Then ultimately,
it's distributed.

00:37:11.630 --> 00:37:14.060
Now it might be distributed
directly into theaters.

00:37:14.060 --> 00:37:17.140
Or if it doesn't
get great reviews

00:37:17.140 --> 00:37:19.460
in the early, early
days of distribution,

00:37:19.460 --> 00:37:21.970
it might actually
go directly to DVD.

00:37:21.970 --> 00:37:25.004
And that's when
Netflix jumps in.

00:37:25.004 --> 00:37:26.920
So if you think about
it, that's a long cycle.

00:37:26.920 --> 00:37:29.460
And I probably skipped 30 parts.

00:37:29.460 --> 00:37:31.660
So where do you fit within
the distribution channel

00:37:31.660 --> 00:37:34.232
is absolutely critical
for you to understand

00:37:34.232 --> 00:37:36.690
how you think about that, and
where you actually capitalize

00:37:36.690 --> 00:37:38.360
and make money.

00:37:38.360 --> 00:37:39.860
Netflix also had
the big challenge

00:37:39.860 --> 00:37:42.840
where they were facing a major
competitor at that time when

00:37:42.840 --> 00:37:44.740
they first came to market.

00:37:44.740 --> 00:37:47.540
Does anybody even remember
who that competitor was?

00:37:47.540 --> 00:37:49.140
AUDIENCE: Blockbuster.

00:37:49.140 --> 00:37:52.870
RICH KIVEL: Blockbuster got
their butt kicked by Netflix.

00:37:52.870 --> 00:37:54.740
What happened?

00:37:54.740 --> 00:37:57.460
What happened was
two major things.

00:37:57.460 --> 00:38:00.420
Number one, technology changed.

00:38:00.420 --> 00:38:03.300
DVDs came out.

00:38:03.300 --> 00:38:05.850
VCRs were going away.

00:38:05.850 --> 00:38:09.070
So videotapes made perfect sense
when you went into Blockbuster.

00:38:09.070 --> 00:38:12.840
It was big, bulky, didn't
even think about shipping it,

00:38:12.840 --> 00:38:13.840
easy to break.

00:38:13.840 --> 00:38:16.450
It gets crushed, doesn't work
so well, tape gets pulled out,

00:38:16.450 --> 00:38:17.280
whatever.

00:38:17.280 --> 00:38:20.170
Blockbuster had a great model.

00:38:20.170 --> 00:38:23.000
They were at the end of the
cycle to us, the consumer.

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:24.940
They put little
stores everywhere.

00:38:24.940 --> 00:38:26.450
And they made it easy.

00:38:26.450 --> 00:38:28.100
But all of a sudden,
the DVD world

00:38:28.100 --> 00:38:29.600
came out, where you
were able to get

00:38:29.600 --> 00:38:32.130
super high-definition
quality picture motion

00:38:32.130 --> 00:38:36.180
pictures on a DVD that is
as flat as an envelope.

00:38:36.180 --> 00:38:38.990
Netflix said, hey,
why are we building

00:38:38.990 --> 00:38:40.280
stores for these things?

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:42.040
People already know
the movie they want.

00:38:42.040 --> 00:38:44.760
Or they could use this new
technology called the internet,

00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:48.340
and figure out what movie they
want, which is mailed to them.

00:38:48.340 --> 00:38:50.780
The other big challenge
that Blockbuster had

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:54.390
was the whole process
of limited supply,

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:57.690
and demand on that supply.

00:38:57.690 --> 00:39:01.220
So they penalized you if you
don't return the video on time

00:39:01.220 --> 00:39:03.270
because they were
losing revenue.

00:39:03.270 --> 00:39:06.320
If you didn't get it put
in that little tiny box

00:39:06.320 --> 00:39:10.261
by 7:00 AM or 10:00 AM the next
morning, you got charged a fee.

00:39:10.261 --> 00:39:10.760
Why?

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:13.290
Because somebody
else wanted their one

00:39:13.290 --> 00:39:16.660
of three copies of that movie.

00:39:16.660 --> 00:39:18.830
They couldn't have
an unlimited supply.

00:39:18.830 --> 00:39:21.150
Whereas the ability
to reproduce and print

00:39:21.150 --> 00:39:23.570
DVDs-- virtually unlimited.

00:39:23.570 --> 00:39:25.100
Everybody in this
room could order

00:39:25.100 --> 00:39:28.830
a DVD today of a hot
movie that just came out.

00:39:28.830 --> 00:39:30.780
It could be at your
house tomorrow.

00:39:30.780 --> 00:39:32.660
There's no distribution issue.

00:39:32.660 --> 00:39:36.170
The ability to reproduce that
DVD, drop it in an envelope,

00:39:36.170 --> 00:39:38.650
and mail it to you is
effortless, completely

00:39:38.650 --> 00:39:40.780
automated.

00:39:40.780 --> 00:39:43.040
So what you have here
is this convergence,

00:39:43.040 --> 00:39:45.500
where there was an opportunity.

00:39:45.500 --> 00:39:47.940
There was technological
change, whether it

00:39:47.940 --> 00:39:50.500
be DVDs or internet or
a combination of both,

00:39:50.500 --> 00:39:54.020
that allowed Netflix to
completely crush Blockbuster.

00:39:54.020 --> 00:39:57.650
And then Netflix changed
themselves, didn't they?

00:39:57.650 --> 00:40:00.170
They recognized that
our ability to capture

00:40:00.170 --> 00:40:03.900
more bandwidth, the ability for
us to actually download a movie

00:40:03.900 --> 00:40:06.510
was increasing in many
parts of the United States,

00:40:06.510 --> 00:40:09.000
not everywhere, not everywhere.

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:11.770
But as our ability,
especially in large cities,

00:40:11.770 --> 00:40:13.992
increased to download
movies-- now all of a sudden,

00:40:13.992 --> 00:40:16.450
it changed to we don't even
have to ship it to you anymore.

00:40:16.450 --> 00:40:18.110
All you have to
do is download it.

00:40:18.110 --> 00:40:20.710
It streams to you.

00:40:20.710 --> 00:40:22.210
And then they created
a whole series

00:40:22.210 --> 00:40:23.501
of other distribution channels.

00:40:23.501 --> 00:40:25.570
Now you can get
Netflix on your Roku.

00:40:25.570 --> 00:40:28.050
You can get Netflix in
all of these other areas.

00:40:28.050 --> 00:40:30.870
So if you think about it, when
the guy that started Netflix

00:40:30.870 --> 00:40:34.210
started off, it was
a very simple model.

00:40:34.210 --> 00:40:35.230
People like movies.

00:40:35.230 --> 00:40:39.120
They're willing to pay for them
so they can watch them at home.

00:40:39.120 --> 00:40:41.280
DVDs are the new thing.

00:40:41.280 --> 00:40:44.930
And we've developed a complex
shipping method and mechanism

00:40:44.930 --> 00:40:47.519
and a model of
warehousing DVDs that we

00:40:47.519 --> 00:40:48.810
can get it to people overnight.

00:40:48.810 --> 00:40:50.040
And they can keep it
for a day, a week.

00:40:50.040 --> 00:40:51.498
We don't really
care, because we're

00:40:51.498 --> 00:40:52.770
going to keep shipping more.

00:40:52.770 --> 00:40:53.830
It was so simple.

00:40:53.830 --> 00:40:55.832
The business model could
not have been easier.

00:40:55.832 --> 00:40:57.290
But what they did
is they continued

00:40:57.290 --> 00:40:59.620
to change and morph
their business model

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:01.420
as the technology changed.

00:41:01.420 --> 00:41:03.740
And they continue to stay
far ahead of the curve.

00:41:03.740 --> 00:41:08.426
What is the latest thing
that Netflix is now doing?

00:41:08.426 --> 00:41:09.550
AUDIENCE: Producing movies.

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:11.091
RICH KIVEL: They're
producing movies.

00:41:11.091 --> 00:41:12.290
How crazy is that?

00:41:12.290 --> 00:41:14.860
But can you imagine if you
were the CEO of Netflix

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:17.450
and you said to the
VCs when you went in

00:41:17.450 --> 00:41:19.930
to talk to them a decade
ago, well here's the thing.

00:41:19.930 --> 00:41:20.890
I got a business idea.

00:41:20.890 --> 00:41:23.223
What we're going to do is,
we're going to basically kick

00:41:23.223 --> 00:41:24.920
Blockbuster's ass.

00:41:24.920 --> 00:41:26.950
We're going to distribute
these things on DVDs.

00:41:26.950 --> 00:41:28.240
And then we're going to
start to do downloadable.

00:41:28.240 --> 00:41:29.615
And then, by the
way, we're going

00:41:29.615 --> 00:41:31.750
to become a movie
production studio.

00:41:31.750 --> 00:41:33.542
Their head would explode.

00:41:33.542 --> 00:41:35.000
And they would just
say, listen you

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:36.490
have no idea what you're doing.

00:41:36.490 --> 00:41:39.430
And you don't understand
how complex the market is.

00:41:39.430 --> 00:41:42.030
That's why earlier
I said, simplicity.

00:41:42.030 --> 00:41:44.290
When you launch your
business, keep it simple.

00:41:44.290 --> 00:41:46.510
Show that that model
is easy to understand.

00:41:46.510 --> 00:41:48.460
And then from there
you continue to expand.

00:41:48.460 --> 00:41:50.910
Who would have thought
Netflix is now producing some

00:41:50.910 --> 00:41:53.750
of the best shows out there?

00:41:53.750 --> 00:41:56.880
Orange Is the New Black is one
of the top shows out there,

00:41:56.880 --> 00:41:59.347
produced by Netflix.

00:41:59.347 --> 00:42:00.680
What are some of the other ones?

00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:01.640
AUDIENCE: House of Cards.

00:42:01.640 --> 00:42:02.764
RICH KIVEL: House of Cards.

00:42:02.764 --> 00:42:05.579
So you think about--
that's mind boggling.

00:42:05.579 --> 00:42:07.870
What is the difference between
Netflix and Blockbuster?

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:13.130
Leadership, the ability
to change, the ability

00:42:13.130 --> 00:42:16.550
to see around the next
curve, and actually

00:42:16.550 --> 00:42:21.367
change the business model of
the company in order to adapt.

00:42:21.367 --> 00:42:23.950
So I'll finish up this area of
revenue generation and margins.

00:42:23.950 --> 00:42:25.533
We talked a little
about that earlier.

00:42:25.533 --> 00:42:27.800
Competitive strategy--
how will the company

00:42:27.800 --> 00:42:30.050
attempt to develop and sustain
a competitor advantage?

00:42:30.050 --> 00:42:31.716
And I've shared a
little bit about that.

00:42:31.716 --> 00:42:32.920
Netflix is a great example.

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:34.420
And then one other
component of this

00:42:34.420 --> 00:42:36.629
is where are you on the field?

00:42:36.629 --> 00:42:38.170
Understanding where
your business is.

00:42:38.170 --> 00:42:40.534
And the Netflix example is
one that is pretty clear.

00:42:40.534 --> 00:42:42.200
When you're over in
this area here where

00:42:42.200 --> 00:42:44.574
you're pilot testing, and
you're in the gestational area,

00:42:44.574 --> 00:42:47.240
or you're doing the roll out,
or you're in slow growth,

00:42:47.240 --> 00:42:51.240
that may not be the time to take
on two or three new business

00:42:51.240 --> 00:42:55.930
models or enter a different part
of the distribution channel.

00:42:55.930 --> 00:42:59.560
But as you start to get
the terminal velocity,

00:42:59.560 --> 00:43:01.700
that's the time when you
start to really look back

00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:03.980
and say, hey, now let's
take a look at our market

00:43:03.980 --> 00:43:05.040
in a different way.

00:43:05.040 --> 00:43:07.760
We've got the velocity, whether
it be the funding, the adoption

00:43:07.760 --> 00:43:08.940
within the marketplace.

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:11.280
And then at that point,
based on the maturity,

00:43:11.280 --> 00:43:13.070
you can start to
think of expanding.

00:43:13.070 --> 00:43:14.672
So where are you on the field?

00:43:14.672 --> 00:43:16.130
It's always important
to know that.

00:43:16.130 --> 00:43:18.320
A lot of companies--
Blockbuster is clearly

00:43:18.320 --> 00:43:21.150
one of them-- that took
their eye off the ball,

00:43:21.150 --> 00:43:23.480
and they just focused
on what they were doing.

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:26.260
And what they did is just
stuff that we look at now.

00:43:26.260 --> 00:43:28.980
We go, gosh, that was so naive.

00:43:28.980 --> 00:43:31.260
You thought maybe
eliminating the late fees is

00:43:31.260 --> 00:43:32.470
going to solve your problem.

00:43:32.470 --> 00:43:35.940
You thought reducing price--
you thought more stores is going

00:43:35.940 --> 00:43:37.770
to-- you look at that now.

00:43:37.770 --> 00:43:40.495
You say, wow, that's the best
that management team could

00:43:40.495 --> 00:43:42.340
come up with.

00:43:42.340 --> 00:43:44.700
They were not stepping
back and saying, where

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:46.420
are we on the field, guys?

00:43:46.420 --> 00:43:49.620
What's happening in the entire
space that we're playing in?

00:43:49.620 --> 00:43:51.320
And where do we play?

00:43:51.320 --> 00:43:53.190
A great example is Google.

00:43:53.190 --> 00:43:56.360
This is a snapshot of the Google
website launched September 4,

00:43:56.360 --> 00:43:58.720
1998.

00:43:58.720 --> 00:44:00.810
Isn't that awesome?

00:44:00.810 --> 00:44:03.975
Has it changed very much?

00:44:03.975 --> 00:44:04.600
Think about it.

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:05.500
How cool is that?

00:44:08.110 --> 00:44:09.660
That is elegant.

00:44:09.660 --> 00:44:10.269
How simple.

00:44:10.269 --> 00:44:10.810
Look at that.

00:44:10.810 --> 00:44:11.740
What is it up there?

00:44:11.740 --> 00:44:18.660
Index contains 25 million
pages, soon to be much bigger.

00:44:18.660 --> 00:44:22.290
How many trillions of pages does
Google have currently indexed?

00:44:22.290 --> 00:44:23.890
Think about that.

00:44:23.890 --> 00:44:27.760
But what's also important think
about is this-- Google could

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:30.890
have state just like this.

00:44:30.890 --> 00:44:34.041
They could have
stayed a simple what?

00:44:34.041 --> 00:44:35.040
AUDIENCE: Search engine.

00:44:35.040 --> 00:44:35.956
RICH KIVEL: That's it.

00:44:35.956 --> 00:44:36.702
Search engine.

00:44:36.702 --> 00:44:38.410
It could have been a
great search engine.

00:44:38.410 --> 00:44:41.140
They could have been a better
search engine than anyone.

00:44:41.140 --> 00:44:42.850
That was what they
were promoting.

00:44:42.850 --> 00:44:45.780
We will find you what you're
looking for faster, better.

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:46.650
We prioritize.

00:44:46.650 --> 00:44:48.020
We have complex algorithms.

00:44:48.020 --> 00:44:49.603
We have a whole bunch
of smart people,

00:44:49.603 --> 00:44:51.580
probably from MIT,
that are helping

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:56.100
you find that weird
shit you're looking for.

00:44:56.100 --> 00:44:57.150
Seriously.

00:44:57.150 --> 00:45:01.370
You're looking for-- you
need a pink doily that

00:45:01.370 --> 00:45:03.440
will be eight inches
that is under a lamp

00:45:03.440 --> 00:45:05.530
for your grandmother's house.

00:45:05.530 --> 00:45:08.410
Or you're looking for
a new hand-held device

00:45:08.410 --> 00:45:09.560
for something else.

00:45:09.560 --> 00:45:11.010
They're going to
find it for you.

00:45:11.010 --> 00:45:12.960
I'm looking to book
a trip to Paris.

00:45:12.960 --> 00:45:16.230
They're going to help prioritize
it, best hotels Paris luxury.

00:45:16.230 --> 00:45:17.960
Put those in, boom.

00:45:17.960 --> 00:45:19.420
Boolean search, we all remember.

00:45:19.420 --> 00:45:24.130
Put in all the complex-- the
word plus this are in quotes.

00:45:24.130 --> 00:45:26.110
They have better
algorithms than Yahoo.

00:45:26.110 --> 00:45:29.140
They have better algorithms than
AltaVista, better algorithms

00:45:29.140 --> 00:45:30.420
than NaviSite.

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:31.960
The list goes on.

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:34.820
They could have stopped
there, and just continued

00:45:34.820 --> 00:45:37.560
to be the best search
engine in the world.

00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:38.310
And you know what?

00:45:38.310 --> 00:45:42.937
They're still killing everybody
in search, killing them.

00:45:42.937 --> 00:45:45.020
People that like Bing or
others probably disagree.

00:45:45.020 --> 00:45:47.810
But I think they kill it.

00:45:47.810 --> 00:45:50.580
But what did they
do as a business?

00:45:50.580 --> 00:45:52.600
Or I should say,
what didn't they

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:57.060
do since 1998 as a business?

00:45:57.060 --> 00:45:59.450
Look at what Google is today.

00:45:59.450 --> 00:46:02.460
Give me a few ideas, one
word from a bunch of you.

00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:05.140
Just what is Google
today besides search?

