It's not the Apple model.

00:57:53.920 --> 00:57:56.206
Who would have thought
years ago-- many of you

00:57:56.206 --> 00:57:58.220
may not even remember,
but years ago there

00:57:58.220 --> 00:58:01.305
was no such thing
as Apple stores.

00:58:01.305 --> 00:58:02.680
How do you buy an
Apple computer?

00:58:02.680 --> 00:58:05.310
Well you bought it
primarily online.

00:58:05.310 --> 00:58:07.770
There were very few
distributors of Apple computers.

00:58:07.770 --> 00:58:09.960
Apple started off selling
to large school systems

00:58:09.960 --> 00:58:10.920
and others.

00:58:10.920 --> 00:58:15.450
And now the Apple Store is as
common in cities in the United

00:58:15.450 --> 00:58:19.750
States and towns as a Starbucks.

00:58:19.750 --> 00:58:23.570
What a different model that
is-- totally mind boggling.

00:58:23.570 --> 00:58:28.050
When most people were moving
away from retail box stores--

00:58:28.050 --> 00:58:32.640
those expensive locations--
and moving to everything

00:58:32.640 --> 00:58:34.290
being internet, Apple
said no, no, no.

00:58:34.290 --> 00:58:36.220
We want to be closer
to the consumer.

00:58:36.220 --> 00:58:38.760
We want the experience
to be superb.

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:41.980
We want them to be part
of this experience.

00:58:41.980 --> 00:58:43.182
They've then opened stores.

00:58:43.182 --> 00:58:45.140
And they're making
tremendous money doing that.

00:58:45.140 --> 00:58:46.910
Who knows Etsy?

00:58:46.910 --> 00:58:48.620
These guys are
cool, aren't they?

00:58:48.620 --> 00:58:50.450
What a neat idea.

00:58:50.450 --> 00:58:54.920
Doing good on a global basis,
something that could never

00:58:54.920 --> 00:58:56.600
been done years ago--
a business model

00:58:56.600 --> 00:58:59.100
where they basically
figured out ways

00:58:59.100 --> 00:59:02.050
to harness the
power of creativity,

00:59:02.050 --> 00:59:05.030
the power of different parts
of the world, people living

00:59:05.030 --> 00:59:07.900
in small villages building
beautiful things that

00:59:07.900 --> 00:59:11.240
would never be seen outside
of probably a 500-mile radius

00:59:11.240 --> 00:59:13.900
of their village,
if that, are now

00:59:13.900 --> 00:59:15.440
part of this very
special network

00:59:15.440 --> 00:59:16.820
where they can build things.

00:59:16.820 --> 00:59:18.020
And you can go online.

00:59:18.020 --> 00:59:19.430
And you can purchase them.

00:59:19.430 --> 00:59:21.300
And a very small
piece is kept by Etsy.

00:59:21.300 --> 00:59:24.710
And most of it goes back to
the artist, to the individual.

00:59:24.710 --> 00:59:27.440
It's phenomenal, the thought
that somebody sitting

00:59:27.440 --> 00:59:32.380
in Peru or Uganda, or somebody
sitting in a far part of Russia

00:59:32.380 --> 00:59:34.860
that builds beautiful
things is actually

00:59:34.860 --> 00:59:38.390
selling them to people
sitting in Japan or in Paris

00:59:38.390 --> 00:59:40.380
or in Boston.

00:59:40.380 --> 00:59:42.570
It's absolutely incredible.

00:59:42.570 --> 00:59:44.870
Other innovative models Zara
is probably my favorite.

00:59:44.870 --> 00:59:47.240
Everybody here knows
Zara at this point.

00:59:47.240 --> 00:59:47.940
I love Spain.

00:59:47.940 --> 00:59:48.730
And I love Zara.

00:59:48.730 --> 00:59:52.430
They're an absolutely
mind boggling story.

00:59:52.430 --> 00:59:55.780
Who thought one company could
innovate an industry that

00:59:55.780 --> 00:59:59.140
has been stagnant and
without innovation

00:59:59.140 --> 01:00:00.140
as the fashion industry?

01:00:00.140 --> 01:00:03.110
The fashion industry has
operated the same way

01:00:03.110 --> 01:00:06.800
for about 100 years.

01:00:06.800 --> 01:00:07.970
They have models.

01:00:07.970 --> 01:00:09.170
They have designers.

01:00:09.170 --> 01:00:10.710
They have magazines.

01:00:10.710 --> 01:00:13.480
The only innovation,
the only innovation

01:00:13.480 --> 01:00:15.840
that's actually hit
the fashion industry

01:00:15.840 --> 01:00:19.320
is they sell some stuff online.

01:00:19.320 --> 01:00:20.720
They outsource manufacturing.

01:00:20.720 --> 01:00:23.190
They've been doing
that for 75 years.

01:00:23.190 --> 01:00:26.480
They have expensive
high-paid designers.

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:29.140
And they basically have
a distribution channel

01:00:29.140 --> 01:00:29.980
through retail.

01:00:29.980 --> 01:00:32.260
It's been exactly the same way.

01:00:32.260 --> 01:00:35.100
The challenge is that many
people who want high fashion

01:00:35.100 --> 01:00:37.060
can't afford high fashion.

01:00:37.060 --> 01:00:39.630
These guys came in and
revolutionized the market.

01:00:39.630 --> 01:00:42.490
And their business model
was harnessed and built

01:00:42.490 --> 01:00:45.110
around time-to-market.

01:00:45.110 --> 01:00:47.060
That is the business model.

01:00:47.060 --> 01:00:50.970
They put people at every
fashion show that's important.

01:00:50.970 --> 01:00:54.620
They're in New York,
Paris, Milan, everywhere.

01:00:54.620 --> 01:00:56.980
And those people are
there taking sketches,

01:00:56.980 --> 01:00:59.970
taking digital photos, and
those things they believe

01:00:59.970 --> 01:01:02.110
the Zara consumer would want.

01:01:02.110 --> 01:01:05.420
Those things are imaged, sent
back instantly to the factory.

01:01:05.420 --> 01:01:10.340
50% of all Zara products
are made in Spain.

01:01:10.340 --> 01:01:11.540
They're sent back.

01:01:11.540 --> 01:01:14.990
They're built. And they're
sent to the stores.

01:01:14.990 --> 01:01:18.626
Virtually none of the
products you find in the Zara

01:01:18.626 --> 01:01:20.250
last in the store
more than four weeks.

01:01:20.250 --> 01:01:22.124
And they will not continue
to replenish them.

01:01:22.124 --> 01:01:25.810
They've created this concept
of scarcity, this concept

01:01:25.810 --> 01:01:28.020
that what you're
buying is high fashion

01:01:28.020 --> 01:01:30.910
and it's in a limited supply.

01:01:30.910 --> 01:01:34.410
That is fantastic, compared
to you go to Macy's.

01:01:34.410 --> 01:01:37.690
And there's 800 of
the same sweaters.

01:01:37.690 --> 01:01:40.130
And there's 8,000 of
the same men's shirts.

01:01:40.130 --> 01:01:44.210
And if I go to a different
Macy's, it's exactly the same.

01:01:44.210 --> 01:01:46.360
There's no sense
of scarcity there.

01:01:46.360 --> 01:01:49.320
Very low design,
very high volume.

01:01:49.320 --> 01:01:52.860
However, if I walk
into the Armani shop

01:01:52.860 --> 01:01:57.540
on Newbury Street or the Fendi
shop, and look at the bags,

01:01:57.540 --> 01:02:01.700
there's a sense of scarcity--
high price, limited resource.

01:02:01.700 --> 01:02:02.760
This is this year's bag.

01:02:02.760 --> 01:02:04.990
This year's jacket.

01:02:04.990 --> 01:02:07.810
Zara basically turned it on its
head and said, no, no, no no.

01:02:07.810 --> 01:02:12.080
We're going to have scarcity
and volume and price.

01:02:12.080 --> 01:02:14.010
And they nailed it
on all of those.

01:02:14.010 --> 01:02:16.430
You don't ever see the Zara
stuff of at Marshalls and T.J.

01:02:16.430 --> 01:02:18.120
Maxx, do you?

01:02:18.120 --> 01:02:20.674
Because they don't
have excess inventory.

01:02:20.674 --> 01:02:22.840
The reason you can walk
into Marshalls and T.J. Maxx

01:02:22.840 --> 01:02:26.230
and pick up Burberry and Cartier
and all these other brands

01:02:26.230 --> 01:02:31.020
is because Bloomingdale's
and Macy's and all of them

01:02:31.020 --> 01:02:31.930
overstocked on them.

01:02:31.930 --> 01:02:32.830
The season changed.

01:02:32.830 --> 01:02:34.580
They don't know what
to do with the stuff.

01:02:34.580 --> 01:02:38.930
So they slash price 60% off, 70%
off, 80% off, then boom, it's

01:02:38.930 --> 01:02:40.875
off to Marshalls.

01:02:40.875 --> 01:02:43.500
And those companies have created
an entirely different business

01:02:43.500 --> 01:02:46.544
model of getting high-quality
goods to consumers.

01:02:46.544 --> 01:02:47.460
Zara said, no, no, no.

01:02:47.460 --> 01:02:49.027
We're not playing that game.

01:02:49.027 --> 01:02:49.860
Let me ask you this.

01:02:49.860 --> 01:02:54.280
When's the last time you saw
a Zara advertisement on TV?

01:02:54.280 --> 01:02:55.630
It doesn't exist.

01:02:55.630 --> 01:03:01.150
When's the last time you saw
a Macy's one-day sale on TV?

01:03:01.150 --> 01:03:02.870
Once a day.

01:03:02.870 --> 01:03:05.280
Entirely different business
model, same industry.

01:03:05.280 --> 01:03:06.170
Zara is amazing.

01:03:06.170 --> 01:03:08.160
I want to finish off
these with Gillette who's

01:03:08.160 --> 01:03:10.210
absolutely just fantastic.

01:03:10.210 --> 01:03:12.530
Gillette, right here
in Massachusetts.

01:03:12.530 --> 01:03:14.360
You see them on your
way to the airport.

01:03:14.360 --> 01:03:17.530
This is the company that created
the concept-- they created

01:03:17.530 --> 01:03:20.190
the first ever disposable
razor, which is a fantastic

01:03:20.190 --> 01:03:21.887
concept, back in the '20s.

01:03:21.887 --> 01:03:23.470
They then decided
that they were going

01:03:23.470 --> 01:03:25.300
to stay at the cutting
edge of technology.

01:03:25.300 --> 01:03:31.810
Gillette has over 1,000 patents
just around the Mach3 razor.

01:03:31.810 --> 01:03:34.930
They have thousands of patents
within their entire portfolio.

01:03:34.930 --> 01:03:39.420
And they will not start
creating a new razor

01:03:39.420 --> 01:03:43.760
until almost a patent life
has expired on the existing

01:03:43.760 --> 01:03:44.810
razors on the market.

01:03:44.810 --> 01:03:47.560
They do not want to
compete against themselves.

01:03:47.560 --> 01:03:48.910
They've created this mechanism.

01:03:48.910 --> 01:03:50.590
It's absolutely mind boggling.

01:03:50.590 --> 01:03:52.550
We get the Mach3
razor as a [? base ?].

01:03:52.550 --> 01:03:55.180
It comes off the assembly
line in the United States.

01:03:55.180 --> 01:03:57.350
If you go to other countries,
especially developing

01:03:57.350 --> 01:03:59.310
countries, they're
getting the razor

01:03:59.310 --> 01:04:03.360
that was hot here five years
ago because they realize

01:04:03.360 --> 01:04:05.650
that they can sell it
for a third of the price

01:04:05.650 --> 01:04:07.140
in large quantities.

01:04:07.140 --> 01:04:09.750
Those countries can't
afford the Mach3.

01:04:09.750 --> 01:04:12.060
But they can afford the one
that was five years ago,

01:04:12.060 --> 01:04:12.950
eight years ago.

01:04:12.950 --> 01:04:15.227
And they're buying
them by the millions.

01:04:15.227 --> 01:04:17.310
And in addition to that,
they created that concept

01:04:17.310 --> 01:04:19.430
of the razor-blade concept.

01:04:19.430 --> 01:04:22.069
It's essentially,
you've got the razor.

01:04:22.069 --> 01:04:24.110
All you have to do is just
keep buying the blades

01:04:24.110 --> 01:04:25.026
and buying the blades.

01:04:25.026 --> 01:04:27.360
And they can charge whatever
they want for the blades.

01:04:27.360 --> 01:04:30.630
Or you have to start fresh
with Schick or somebody else.

01:04:30.630 --> 01:04:35.620
So it's a fantastic concept
of high quality, patents

01:04:35.620 --> 01:04:37.880
there in order to
maintain their position

01:04:37.880 --> 01:04:43.060
within the marketplace, and
also customer stickiness.

01:04:43.060 --> 01:04:44.490
We gave them this pretty razor.

01:04:44.490 --> 01:04:45.150
It's beautiful.

01:04:45.150 --> 01:04:46.100
It's got metal on it.

01:04:46.100 --> 01:04:47.230
It's got nice colors.

01:04:47.230 --> 01:04:49.105
They're just going to
keep buying the blades,

01:04:49.105 --> 01:04:50.980
buying the blades,
and buying the blades.

01:04:50.980 --> 01:04:53.120
So it's a fantastic series
of different business

01:04:53.120 --> 01:04:54.544
models within one.

01:04:54.544 --> 01:04:55.960
Other ones we're
all familiar with

01:04:55.960 --> 01:04:57.550
are great groups
like Kickstarter,

01:04:57.550 --> 01:05:02.410
PayPal are really leveraging
the whole P2P revolution.

01:05:02.410 --> 01:05:03.990
It's absolutely
amazing what you see.

01:05:03.990 --> 01:05:06.470
Craig's List is a
fantastic example of that.

01:05:06.470 --> 01:05:09.600
Their website is about as
sexy as the Google page.

01:05:09.600 --> 01:05:11.430
There's really nothing
attractive about it.

01:05:11.430 --> 01:05:13.660
But it's an incredibly
successful business.

01:05:13.660 --> 01:05:14.920
We talked about Dell.

01:05:14.920 --> 01:05:16.570
They built their
entire success around

01:05:16.570 --> 01:05:18.060
the just-in-time concept.

01:05:18.060 --> 01:05:21.240
We're going to build a computer
exactly the way you want it.

01:05:21.240 --> 01:05:24.820
In addition to that, you've got
the one day, one deal business

01:05:24.820 --> 01:05:25.750
model.

01:05:25.750 --> 01:05:27.410
We're all familiar
with our inboxes

01:05:27.410 --> 01:05:30.290
full of Living Social
and Groupon and all

01:05:30.290 --> 01:05:31.187
these other groups.

01:05:31.187 --> 01:05:33.020
In addition to that,
you've got other groups

01:05:33.020 --> 01:05:36.280
like Priceline, which I think is
a phenomenal model, and really

01:05:36.280 --> 01:05:37.379
unique advertising too.

01:05:37.379 --> 01:05:39.670
They've taken an approach,
unlike a lot of these groups

01:05:39.670 --> 01:05:42.160
here who you never see on TV.

01:05:42.160 --> 01:05:45.020
Priceline has taken the approach
of using somebody like Shatner

01:05:45.020 --> 01:05:48.450
or other people that basically
get them excited about-- you

01:05:48.450 --> 01:05:50.560
set your price,
you're in control.

01:05:50.560 --> 01:05:51.836
And some of us love that.

01:05:51.836 --> 01:05:52.960
Some people love Priceline.

01:05:52.960 --> 01:05:55.830
I have friends that use
Priceline all of the time.

01:05:55.830 --> 01:05:56.940
Some of us just jump on.

01:05:56.940 --> 01:05:58.190
And we just go to expedia.com.

01:05:58.190 --> 01:05:59.556
And we book our hotel.

01:05:59.556 --> 01:06:01.180
Or we go to the new
one, Hotel Tonight,

01:06:01.180 --> 01:06:02.710
which is my favorite
app, especially when I'm

01:06:02.710 --> 01:06:04.120
going to different cities.

01:06:04.120 --> 01:06:06.770
You jump onto Hotel Tonight,
entirely different model.

01:06:06.770 --> 01:06:11.260
They only list hotels after
12:00 in the afternoon.

01:06:11.260 --> 01:06:15.140
They cut these special deals
with the hotels for that night.

01:06:15.140 --> 01:06:17.530
So you wind up staying
at fantastic places

01:06:17.530 --> 01:06:20.330
because they knew at 11:55
they had availability.

01:06:20.330 --> 01:06:22.140
They released the
rooms to Hotel Tonight.

01:06:22.140 --> 01:06:26.550
Hotel Tonight kills hotels.com,
another one, that day.

01:06:26.550 --> 01:06:29.261
It might not be the way to
book a seven-day vacation.

01:06:29.261 --> 01:06:31.510
But if you're looking for
two nights in New York City,

01:06:31.510 --> 01:06:32.310
it's phenomenal.

01:06:32.310 --> 01:06:34.930
It's all on your app,
not on the website.

01:06:34.930 --> 01:06:37.020
You can't even do
it on the website.

01:06:37.020 --> 01:06:39.180
Uber's another fantastic
example of that.

01:06:39.180 --> 01:06:41.890
Instant gratification,
car-service quality,

01:06:41.890 --> 01:06:46.120
not a taxi cab, all
web-based, all app-based.

01:06:46.120 --> 01:06:49.670
So to summarize, value
proposition, market segment

01:06:49.670 --> 01:06:52.080
and value chain are really
understandings that you

01:06:52.080 --> 01:06:55.577
have to have in this area of
developing a business model.

01:06:55.577 --> 01:06:56.910
Where do you sit in the network?

01:06:56.910 --> 01:06:58.570
Exactly where are
you on the field?

01:06:58.570 --> 01:07:00.440
And revenue generation
and margins-- those

01:07:00.440 --> 01:07:01.330
are two different things.

01:07:01.330 --> 01:07:02.990
You have to think about
what's important to you.

01:07:02.990 --> 01:07:04.781
Are you going to be a
high-margin business,

01:07:04.781 --> 01:07:05.290
low volume?

01:07:05.290 --> 01:07:07.740
Are you going to be a
high-revenue business

01:07:07.740 --> 01:07:08.684
and low margin?

01:07:08.684 --> 01:07:10.600
Or are you going to try
to do what Apple does,

01:07:10.600 --> 01:07:12.237
which is a combination of both?

01:07:12.237 --> 01:07:14.320
Where do you fit within
the competitive landscape?

01:07:14.320 --> 01:07:16.320
And of course, the stage of
development of your company

01:07:16.320 --> 01:07:16.980
is critical.

01:07:16.980 --> 01:07:21.400
Where are you within that
particular growth cycle?

01:07:21.400 --> 01:07:23.720
And always remember
that success consists

01:07:23.720 --> 01:07:25.180
from going from
failure to failure

01:07:25.180 --> 01:07:26.845
without a loss of enthusiasm.

01:07:26.845 --> 01:07:27.720
And I'll close there.

01:07:27.720 --> 01:07:28.920
Thank you all.

01:07:28.920 --> 01:07:30.625
[APPLAUSE]

